<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870518-0152 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor:Outsider Information</HL><DD> 05/18/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> AA </IN><TEXT>   Your April 21 story states: &quot;For the first time in its 99-year history, Aluminum Company of America reached outside the company to fill its top post, naming Paul H. O'Neill chairman and chief executive officer.&quot;    Upon the death in 1899 of Alfred E. Hunt, the company's first president, Richard B. Mellon -- a Pittsburgh banker -- was elected president. He held that position until 1910. At the time the president was the top officer of the company.    Edward B. Foote   Oakmont, Pa.</TEXT></DOC>